1327","1348":"1348","1425":"1425","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1279":"1279","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","about 1323":"circa 1323","Of, Malley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hope, Derbyshire, England":"Hope, Derbyshire, England","Of, Monkspath, Warwickshire, England":"Monkspath, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1315–1375":"about 1315–1375","1315–1375":"1315–1375","1310–1372":"1310–1372","1322–Male":"1322–Deceased","1323–Male":"1323–Deceased","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1327–1425":"1327–1425","1348–1380":"1348–1380","1285–Male":"1285–Deceased","1279–Female":"1279–Deceased","Abt 1315":"about 1315","Abt 1325":"about 1325","1285":"1285","1372":"1372","Abt 1323":"about 1323","1 July 1372":"1 July 1372","1380":"1380","1327":"1327","1348":"1348","1425":"1425","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1279":"1279","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","about 1323":"about 1323","Of, Malley, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Hope, Derbyshire, England":"Hope, Derbyshire, England","Of, Monkspath, Warwickshire, England":"Monkspath, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Malley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Malley  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in northern France called Mailly (Marne, Somme, and elsewhere).","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Mlej</b> (see   Malay  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Maley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Malley   (see   O'Malley  ).","Americanized form of Rusyn (from Slovakia) <b>Mlej</b> (see   Malay   1).","Americanized form of Czech and Slovak <b>Malý</b>, Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1), or Slovenian   Mali   ‘small, little’. Compare   Maly   4 and   Malley   4."]},{"name":"Manley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Devon and Cheshire, named in Old English as ‘common wood or clearing’, from <i>(ge)mǣne</i> ‘common, shared’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The surname is still chiefly found in the regions around these villages.","English: nickname from Middle English<i>mannly</i> ‘manly, virile, brave’ (Old English<i>mannlīc</i>, originally ‘man-like’).","Irish (County Cork): Anglicized form of <b>Ó Máinle</b> (and often pronounced <i>Mauly</i>), of unexplained etymology. Compare   Malley  ."]},{"name":"O'Malley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Colm, Cormac, Brigid, Cahal, Colum, Conal, Conor, Delma, Donal, Eamon.","Irish (Mayo and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Máille</b>. This is of uncertain derivation. Woulfe suggests a Celtic source <i>maglios</i> ‘prince, champion, poet’. There is a Gaelic adjective <i>mall</i> ‘slow, stately’, and another, <i>málla</i>, meaning ‘sedate, pleasant’, and an abstract noun <i>máille</i> ‘stateliness’; the source could be any of these."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Malley was born about 1315, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Malley, was 32 and her mother, Mary, was 37. She married Thomas Archer about 1323. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1375, at the age of 61."},"et":{"Abt 1315–1375":"umbes 1315–1375","1315–1375":"1315–1375","1310–1372":"1310–1372","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1323–Male":"1323–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1327–1425":"1327–1425","134